00:10:51.680 --> 00:10:56.010
&gt;&gt; Margaret Barker: Well, today we
have laws protecting wild birds,

00:10:56.010 --> 00:11:01.490
importantly the Migratory Bird
Treaty Act signed in 1918.

00:11:01.490 --> 00:11:06.200
But in the late 1800's
U.S. birds were in trouble.

00:11:06.200 --> 00:11:10.870
Backyard birds like cardinals could
be caged and sold as song birds.

00:11:10.870 --> 00:11:14.750
Birds were killed for their
feathers for women's hats and more.

00:11:14.750 --> 00:11:17.810
And species of all
kinds were on the menu.

00:11:17.810 --> 00:11:19.960
And they were over hunted.

00:11:19.960 --> 00:11:24.160
Scientists studied birds'
economic value and usefulness.

00:11:24.160 --> 00:11:28.790
Bird feeding helped teach people
about their bird neighbors.

00:11:28.790 --> 00:11:32.460
And the case was made that
if you feed good birds,

00:11:32.460 --> 00:11:36.810
they'll return the favor and
stay around your home and farm

00:11:36.810 --> 00:11:41.290
and eat weed seeds
and harmful insects.

00:11:41.290 --> 00:11:43.540
Professor Beal, in
the U.S. Department

00:11:43.540 --> 00:11:49.800 position:56%
of Agriculture's Biological Survey
Division, documented what birds ate.

00:11:49.800 --> 00:11:55.010
His "Farmer's Bulletin Number
54" was in print for many years.

00:11:55.010 --> 00:11:58.790
His colleague, Waldo McAtee,
summed up Beal's importance

00:11:58.790 --> 00:12:03.600
to birds this way: "He did
more than any other man

00:12:03.600 --> 00:12:07.930
to reveal the basic facts that were
needed to convince the so-called

00:12:07.930 --> 00:12:12.230
"practical" men of the
value of bird protection."

00:12:12.230 --> 00:12:14.780
&gt;&gt; Paul Baicich: As
Margaret just indicated,

00:12:14.780 --> 00:12:18.220
this economic ornithology,
as it was called,

00:12:18.220 --> 00:12:20.130
was connected to agriculture.

00:12:20.130 --> 00:12:22.680
There were good birds
and there were bad birds.

00:12:22.680 --> 00:12:24.410
There were birds that
were advantageous

00:12:24.410 --> 00:12:26.560
to the farmer and disadvantageous.

00:12:26.560 --> 00:12:28.780
And it's important to appreciate

00:12:28.780 --> 00:12:33.030
that primitive attitude
towards science and the economy

00:12:33.030 --> 00:12:35.140
in comparison to what we do today.

00:12:35.140 --> 00:12:38.510
And part of the change occurred
during the bird preservation

00:12:38.510 --> 00:12:43.740
movement, that birds, in and
of themselves, had value.

00:12:43.740 --> 00:12:49.090
The movement to ban the trade
of birds, and to save them,

00:12:49.090 --> 00:12:54.600
and to make sure that they were
persistent into the future rotated

00:12:54.600 --> 00:13:00.550
around the effort to ban the
feather trade in particular.

00:13:00.550 --> 00:13:03.470
Florence Merriam Bailey is a good
characteristic and representative

00:13:03.470 --> 00:13:07.780 position:56%
of that woman's movement by and
large and representative of the era.

00:13:07.780 --> 00:13:13.670
In 1886, as a student at Smith
College in Massachusetts,

00:13:13.670 --> 00:13:19.600
she recruited hundreds of
her colleagues, young women,

00:13:19.600 --> 00:13:23.350
to form an Audubon Society
to stop the feather trade.

00:13:23.350 --> 00:13:27.010
By thirteen years later she
had matured to such a level

00:13:27.010 --> 00:13:30.450
that when she moved to Washington,
D.C., with her brother, here,

00:13:30.450 --> 00:13:33.440
Washington, D.C., her brother
by the way was C. Hart Merriam,

00:13:33.440 --> 00:13:37.730
who headed the U.S. Biological
Survey, the predecessor

00:13:37.730 --> 00:13:39.530
to Fish and Wildlife Service.

00:13:39.530 --> 00:13:43.500
She was able in 1898 to lead
classes here in Washington,

00:13:43.500 --> 00:13:46.930
D.C. about the value of
birds and the appreciation.

00:13:46.930 --> 00:13:51.350
And that very same year she
had published "Birds of Village

00:13:51.350 --> 00:13:57.120
and Field," which introduced
many, many people to the interest

00:13:57.120 --> 00:14:01.040
and curiosity of bird life and
the possibility of feeding them.

00:14:01.040 --> 00:14:05.220
The same time her female
colleagues such as [Inaudible],

00:14:05.220 --> 00:14:09.190
Mabel Osgood Wright, and Oliver
Thorne Miller were doing similar

00:14:09.190 --> 00:14:11.400
and parallel activities.

00:14:11.400 --> 00:14:14.300
The bird preservation
movement stopped the slaughter

00:14:14.300 --> 00:14:16.310
with the 1900 Lacey Act.

00:14:16.310 --> 00:14:19.180 position:56%
They were successful and, by the
way, this was a woman's led movement

00:14:19.180 --> 00:14:23.260
when the women didn't even
have the right to vote.

00:14:23.260 --> 00:14:27.990
In this effort to adorn female garb

00:14:27.990 --> 00:14:32.540
with feathers the entire bird
was killed, in this case, egrets,

00:14:32.540 --> 00:14:35.860
for one plume of the hat.

00:14:35.860 --> 00:14:38.970
The destruction of
colonies, because these kinds

00:14:38.970 --> 00:14:42.660
of feathers only appeared when
birds were in breeding plumage,

00:14:42.660 --> 00:14:45.720
the entire destruction
of colonies and the death

00:14:45.720 --> 00:14:49.630
of young were a byproduct of that.

00:14:49.630 --> 00:14:56.600
But it stopped with the passage
of the Lacey Act of 1900.

00:14:56.600 --> 00:15:01.470
&gt;&gt; Margaret Barker: So the study
