00:39:43.100 --> 00:39:47.280
We'll go to, very quickly, the
collective wisdom and experience

00:39:47.280 --> 00:39:50.340 position:56%
of 120 years, the five major lessons

00:39:50.340 --> 00:39:53.070
that have been necessarily
accumulated.

00:39:53.070 --> 00:39:59.110
The story of bird feeding
reduced down to a bouillon cube,

00:39:59.110 --> 00:40:01.330
or at least five bouillon cubes.

00:40:01.330 --> 00:40:05.190
Bird feeding in four seasons;
providing water in four seasons;

00:40:05.190 --> 00:40:08.870 position:56%
offering a variety of food;
providing protection from predators;

00:40:08.870 --> 00:40:11.760
and clean feeders and
ground areas regularly.

00:40:11.760 --> 00:40:16.010 position:56%
We show old fashioned stuff on the
left and the new stuff on the right.

00:40:16.010 --> 00:40:22.440
First, in terms of five ways of
feeding success, all four seasons.

00:40:22.440 --> 00:40:26.480
When we began this narrative it was
mainly feeding in the wintertime

00:40:26.480 --> 00:40:29.060
and it still is mainly
feeding in the wintertime.

00:40:29.060 --> 00:40:33.340
But, you know, in Florida, in
Texas, and southern California,

00:40:33.340 --> 00:40:37.360
and southeast Arizona wintertime
isn't as tough as it is up here

00:40:37.360 --> 00:40:42.820
for some reason and they can feed
all year and they do feed all year.

00:40:42.820 --> 00:40:45.760
And they weren't just
limited to wintertime feeding,

00:40:45.760 --> 00:40:48.900
indeed you'll notice that
the feeding has changed

00:40:48.900 --> 00:40:53.840
from the old hopper feeder with the
requisite trim and evergreen here,

00:40:53.840 --> 00:40:59.050
shown from the nineteen teen's,
to the feeder here in summertime

00:40:59.050 --> 00:41:00.650
with multiple different kinds

00:41:00.650 --> 00:41:04.430
of food including fruits
and different levels.

00:41:04.430 --> 00:41:06.030
Next.

00:41:06.030 --> 00:41:09.290
&gt;&gt; Margaret Barker: Water of course
is essential for backyard birds

00:41:09.290 --> 00:41:12.480
and it's fun to watch
them drink and bathe.

00:41:12.480 --> 00:41:16.740
Birdbaths go back as far as
the ancient Greeks and Romans.

00:41:16.740 --> 00:41:19.920
Water attracts more
than feeder species.

00:41:19.920 --> 00:41:22.950
You might find bathing
warblers, too, for example,

00:41:22.950 --> 00:41:25.120
especially this time of year.

00:41:25.120 --> 00:41:29.540
Moving water especially
brings in the birds.

00:41:29.540 --> 00:41:32.410
&gt;&gt; Paul Baicich: The next way is to
provide protection from predators,

00:41:32.410 --> 00:41:36.930
in this case -- oh, I'm sorry
-- the next case is -- .

00:41:36.930 --> 00:41:39.240
&gt;&gt; Margaret Barker:
Carrol's suggested backyard.

00:41:39.240 --> 00:41:43.780
This was developed by Carrol
Henderson, our co-author.

00:41:43.780 --> 00:41:46.690
You can see a black and
white image of a backyard

00:41:46.690 --> 00:41:50.950
from about the 1920's on the left.

00:41:50.950 --> 00:41:54.950
And on the right is Carrol
Henderson's backyard.

00:41:54.950 --> 00:42:00.880
He says if you can do it and
you want to get a lot of birds,

00:42:00.880 --> 00:42:06.280
use a total of twelve to fifteen
feeders of many different types

00:42:06.280 --> 00:42:11.500
in groups of three to four each
and offer a wide range of foods

00:42:11.500 --> 00:42:15.690
from different kinds of
seeds to suet, grape jelly,

00:42:15.690 --> 00:42:21.980
apple and orange slices,
meal worms, and sugar water.

00:42:21.980 --> 00:42:24.640
&gt;&gt; Paul Biacich: Next indeed is to
provide protection from predators,

00:42:24.640 --> 00:42:27.370
in this case, in one case, cats.

00:42:27.370 --> 00:42:29.800 position:56%
The picture on the left shows Tabby.

00:42:29.800 --> 00:42:34.120
This is Edward Howe Forbush's
experiment of putting a bird

00:42:34.120 --> 00:42:37.810
that Tabby killed, a warbler, a
yellow warbler I believe it was,

00:42:37.810 --> 00:42:43.490
around the neck of poor Tabby
to teach it a lesson and to keep

00:42:43.490 --> 00:42:48.560 position:56%
that dead, stinking bird around
Tabby's neck for days, if not weeks.

00:42:48.560 --> 00:42:51.870
Needless to say, it didn't work.

00:42:51.870 --> 00:42:56.700
But Forbush, in 1960, wrote the
classic piece, "The Domestic Cat:

00:42:56.700 --> 00:42:59.750
Bird killer, mouser, and
destroyer of wildlife.

00:42:59.750 --> 00:43:02.750
Means of utilizing
and controlling it."

00:43:02.750 --> 00:43:05.760
Well, there's decent
ways to control it.

00:43:05.760 --> 00:43:10.230
One method is to maintain a
ten foot clearance around sites

00:43:10.230 --> 00:43:13.800
that are hiding place free in
terms of a ten foot clearance

00:43:13.800 --> 00:43:15.320
around your bird feeders.

00:43:15.320 --> 00:43:18.400
The opposite is to encircle
the site with wire fencing.

00:43:18.400 --> 00:43:22.680
That keeps the bird feeder
from becoming a cat feeder.

00:43:22.680 --> 00:43:25.890
Similarly, the next case
is to provide protection

00:43:25.890 --> 00:43:29.870
from predators using
good brush piles,

00:43:29.870 --> 00:43:34.070
offering the birds quick
escapes from sky borne perils,

00:43:34.070 --> 00:43:36.090
either Cooper's hawks

00:43:36.090 --> 00:43:38.730
or Sharp-shinned hawks
visiting the feeders.

00:43:38.730 --> 00:43:41.990
Birds do take readily
to these brush piles.

00:43:41.990 --> 00:43:47.840
And if you keep the brush piles,
again, away from the feeders,

00:43:47.840 --> 00:43:50.270
about ten feet away,
it also keeps them

00:43:50.270 --> 00:43:53.410
from being hiding places for cats.

00:43:53.410 --> 00:43:58.230
&gt;&gt; Margaret Barker: The latest bird
feeder designs are easy to clean

00:43:58.230 --> 00:44:02.620
and this is good news because
people who have been feeding birds

00:44:02.620 --> 00:44:05.770
