00:49:30.660 --> 00:49:34.180
&gt;&gt; I vaguely recall, maybe 30
years ago, reading that the spread

00:49:34.180 --> 00:49:38.140
of feeding had some effect on,
for example, northern cardinals,

00:49:38.140 --> 00:49:40.220
the winter range as far
as the north [inaudible].

00:49:40.220 --> 00:49:42.140
Are there other dramatic
effects like that,

00:49:42.140 --> 00:49:45.530
the distribution of animals?

00:49:45.530 --> 00:49:47.390
&gt;&gt; Paul Baicich: Well,
probably feeder-wise,

00:49:47.390 --> 00:49:50.980
it's probably not dependent
on but it probably helps.

00:49:50.980 --> 00:49:54.560
I would include -- cardinals
would be among the first

00:49:54.560 --> 00:49:57.300
which would have been starting
over a hundred years ago

00:49:57.300 --> 00:49:58.740
when they started moving north.

00:49:58.740 --> 00:50:02.100
But other southern birds that have
moved north and have been helped

00:50:02.100 --> 00:50:08.570
by feeders have been tufted
titmouse, red bellied woodpecker,

00:50:08.570 --> 00:50:12.740
and probably Carolina wren in so
far as that they come to suet.

00:50:12.740 --> 00:50:16.090
And the Carolina wrens
are an example

00:50:16.090 --> 00:50:20.250
of blizzard threatened birds.

00:50:20.250 --> 00:50:23.410
In New England when
it's a tough, tough,

00:50:23.410 --> 00:50:27.370
tough winter the Carolina
wrens, having just reached,

00:50:27.370 --> 00:50:32.340
"just" reached New England
maybe in the 1980's and 90's,

00:50:32.340 --> 00:50:34.710
they're hammered back when
in very difficult winters

00:50:34.710 --> 00:50:38.350
and it may take a few years or
half a decade for them to recover.

00:50:38.350 --> 00:50:41.450
So in that case, you know, a
feeding station might be important

00:50:41.450 --> 00:50:46.380
for your Carolina wrens if
you live in Vermont or Maine.

00:50:46.380 --> 00:50:49.870
But otherwise I don't think there's
much that we can attribute in terms

00:50:49.870 --> 00:50:55.090
of northern spread
having to do with feeders.

00:50:55.090 --> 00:50:57.420
I think there is a western spread

00:50:57.420 --> 00:51:00.840
when we're dealing
with house finches.

00:51:00.840 --> 00:51:04.330
And I think house finches
have really been accelerated

00:51:04.330 --> 00:51:08.800
and accommodated by feeding
stations as they've moved west.

