00:55:18.150 --> 00:55:20.210
&gt;&gt; There was, you showed
a device meant

00:55:20.210 --> 00:55:22.080
to discourage English sparrows.

00:55:22.080 --> 00:55:25.110
Are the same little brown
sparrows that we have everywhere?

00:55:25.110 --> 00:55:26.410
&gt;&gt; Paul Baicich: Yes.

00:55:26.410 --> 00:55:29.000
The English sparrows are now called
house sparrows, were introduced

00:55:29.000 --> 00:55:39.170
to Brooklyn, New York, 1850, 1852,
I think two or three releases.

00:55:39.170 --> 00:55:43.490
And it was thought that
they would eat gypsy moths

00:55:43.490 --> 00:55:44.790
and gypsy moth worms.

00:55:44.790 --> 00:55:46.840
It didn't work.

00:55:46.840 --> 00:55:49.350
They spread all over the country.

00:55:49.350 --> 00:55:53.960
They became bullies to other
birds and became undesirable.

00:55:53.960 --> 00:55:58.170 position:56%
This was a device not to discourage,
you wisely used the word,

00:55:58.170 --> 00:56:00.800
or politically correct to
use the word discourage.

00:56:00.800 --> 00:56:05.950
This was a device to capture so
you could dispose of these birds.

00:56:05.950 --> 00:56:09.190
Curiously they have been
declining over the last,

00:56:09.190 --> 00:56:11.740
house sparrows have been declining
over the last 30, 40 years.

00:56:11.740 --> 00:56:15.460
And that's particularly because
of the decline of the horse.

00:56:15.460 --> 00:56:18.950
In urban areas, in cities
house sparrows flourished

00:56:18.950 --> 00:56:23.040
because of spilled grain and
feeding horses, oats in particular.

00:56:23.040 --> 00:56:27.380
Also they would recycle the
manure that wasn't fully,

00:56:27.380 --> 00:56:30.420
necessarily digested by
the horse on city streets.

00:56:30.420 --> 00:56:31.720
House sparrows would do very well.

00:56:31.720 --> 00:56:33.530
They don't do that well now.

00:56:33.530 --> 00:56:36.290
They may be in some urban areas
including Washington, D.C.,

00:56:36.290 --> 00:56:39.990
and maybe your backyard but
they are highly reduced.

00:56:39.990 --> 00:56:42.210
Margaret, did you get
the results from -- ?

00:56:42.210 --> 00:56:44.290
&gt;&gt; Margaret Barker: Also
in Europe they're declining

00:56:44.290 --> 00:56:49.290 position:56%
and it's remarkable because a lot of
people who put up birdhouses don't

00:56:49.290 --> 00:56:50.590
like house sparrows a lot.

00:56:50.590 --> 00:56:53.770
They can be very aggressive,
especially toward bluebirds.

00:56:53.770 --> 00:56:59.030
And, but you can go online and
see people in England weeping

00:56:59.030 --> 00:57:03.010
about the decline in
house sparrow populations.

00:57:03.010 --> 00:57:06.980
House sparrows are not a
protected bird in this country.

00:57:06.980 --> 00:57:11.230
They're not protected under
the Migratory Bird Treaty Act.

00:57:11.230 --> 00:57:12.530 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Paul Baicich: They're not native.

00:57:12.530 --> 00:57:13.890
They're not native just like
starlings are not native birds.

00:57:13.890 --> 00:57:15.190
They're not protected.

00:57:15.190 --> 00:57:20.810
So they are disposed of and
dispatched accordingly many places.

